---
import ApplicationLayout from '../layouts/ApplicationLayout.astro';

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: "What is a disc stack centrifuge?",
    answer: "A disc stack centrifuge is a high-speed rotating separator that uses centrifugal force (7,000\u201312,000 Gs) to separate liquids of different densities, or to remove fine solid particles from a liquid. The bowl contains a stack of conical metal discs that multiply the settling area, enabling separation of particles as small as 0.5\u20131 micron. It is used for oil clarification, coolant recovery, wastewater polishing, and food/beverage processing."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between a self-cleaning and a manual-clean disc centrifuge?",
    answer: "A self-cleaning (automatic) disc centrifuge ejects accumulated sludge automatically at timed intervals by briefly opening ports at the bowl periphery, allowing continuous unattended operation. A manual-clean centrifuge must be stopped and disassembled to remove accumulated solids. Self-cleaning centrifuges are preferred for high-solids applications or processes requiring 24/7 uptime."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I select the right disc stack centrifuge size?",
    answer: "Disc stack centrifuge sizing depends on: (1) required flow rate in GPM or LPH, (2) percentage of solids in the feed, (3) target separation quality, (4) fluid viscosity and temperature, and (5) available utilities. Dolphin Centrifuge\u2019s DMPX series ranges from 7 GPM (DMPX-010) to 59\u201372 GPM (DMPX-070). Contact Dolphin Centrifuge for a sizing recommendation based on your specific process parameters."
  },
  {
    question: "How much does a disc stack centrifuge cost?",
    answer: "A small-capacity disc centrifuge from a name-brand OEM starts at around $15,000 for a bare centrifuge. With options such as a skid, control system, wiring, and alarms, costs reach $40,000 or more. High-capacity food-grade centrifuges can exceed $750,000. Re-manufactured disc centrifuges cost 40\u201360% of new machines of similar capacity."
  },
  {
    question: "What are the advantages of a disc stack centrifuge over filtration?",
    answer: "Disc stack centrifuges separate both solids and water in a single pass without consumable filter media. They remove particles down to 1 micron, maintain consistent throughput without clogging, and have negligible operating and disposal costs. The total cost of ownership is typically lower than filtration, with upfront costs recovered within 1\u20132 years."
  }
];

