  <!-- AI Summary — 30-50 words -->
  <div class="not-prose bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies industrial disc stack centrifuge systems for high-speed liquid-liquid-solid separation. Operating at 7,000&ndash;12,000 Gs, these self-cleaning separators process 5 to 100+ GPM continuously, separating particles from 0.5 microns. Over 40 years of disc stack centrifuge experience.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Intro -->
  <p>
    A disc stack centrifuge is a specifically designed <a href="/industrial-centrifuge/">industrial centrifuge</a> with a stack of cone-shaped discs. The additional surface increases the settling area multi-fold and reduces the settling distance. Combined with high g-force (7,000 Gs), these features make it a highly efficient separation device for fine particles (0.5&micro;m) and immiscible liquids.
  </p>
  <p>
    A disc stack centrifuge is also known as a <em>disc bowl, conical plate, disk stack, or disc stack separator.</em>
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img
      src="/images/disc-stack-centrifuge/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-bowl-cross-section-600-1.webp"
      alt="Alfa Laval Disc Stack Centrifuge Bowl Section"
      width="600" height="333"
      loading="lazy"
      class="img-cap-600"
    />
    <figcaption>Alfa Laval Disc Centrifuge Bowl Cross Section</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <!-- Operation -->
  <h2 id="operation">Operation</h2>

  <figure>
    <img
      src="/images/shared/Disc-Centrifuge-Self-Cleaning-Animation-600.gif"
      alt="Disc Centrifuge Self Cleaning Animation"
      width="599" height="460"
      loading="lazy"
      class="img-cap-600"
    />
    <figcaption>Disc Centrifuge Self-Cleaning Animation</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    A disc-stack centrifuge separates immiscible liquids and suspended solids from contaminated fluids. G-forces up to 10,000 Gs cause the particles' sedimentation on the disc surface where they flocculate and move toward the centrifuge bowl periphery.
  </p>
  <p>
    The accumulated solids are self-ejected or manually removed from the disc centrifuge bowl.
  </p>
  <p>
    Think of the discs in the centrifuge bowl splitting the liquid column into thin slices between the inter-disc space. The rotating discs impart the rotational velocity to the incoming stationary (non-rotating) fluid quickly due to the liquid's viscosity.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img
      src="/images/disc-stack-centrifuge/disc-stack-bowl-disc-spacing-1000-768x307-1.webp"
      alt="disc stack showing inter disc spacing"
      width="768" height="307"
      loading="lazy"
      class="img-cap-800"
    />
    <figcaption>Disc stack showing inter-disc spacing</figcaption>
  </figure>

